lyScreenFromWeb?topicID=564.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Return to the Shadows</span><hr size=1> The pass echoed with the sounds of steel on steel, screams of the dying Orcs and Gnolls that adventurers slaughtered to make a name for themselves. The guards at the gate to the Keep made bets on how many of the young wannabe's would come running to them with a train of beasts hot on their tails.<br>
<br>
The many dark shadows in the mountain pass provided the cover she needed as Terolyn crept past the ledge occupied by the Gnolls. She did no fear the dog-like beasts, but she did not have time to play with them today either. There were other matters at hand that needed attending to.<br>
<br>
Hidden in the shadows she made her way through the winding, and often confusion, trails of the mountain pass. Though she loathed to be here, she knew the pass well enough that she no longer got lost and was soon standing outside the Lion’s Roar. She quickened her pace slightly as she stepped onto the fisherman’s wharf outside the inn, and taking a deep breath she plunged into the icy water that gave the residents of the pass their water. <br>
<br>
Terolyn sliced easily through the water, diving deep beneath the surface to a cave near the floor of the lake. She swam through the narrow tunnel that lead into an area of the pass closed off from the rest. The smuggler guarding the watery entrance eyed her questioningly as she broke the water’s surface, but otherwise ignored her as she climbed out of the water. <br>
<br>
Nimble fingers ran through ginger hair, ridding it of as much water as she could before tying it back away from her face again. It had been some time since she had been to the smuggler’s cove of High Hold Pass, but she remembered the way.<br>
<br>
And as she had expected, she had no sooner stepped into the open area of the cove than a voice echoed against the mountain walls.<br>
<br>
&quot; Anari Ravensblade, I heard you were dead.&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn smirked and turned to face the human that approached her. &quot; Which time, McBale?&quot; <br>
<br>
Anson McBale, the smuggler lord, chuckled and came to stand before her. &quot; It’s been some time, Rogue, since you last graced us with your presence.&quot;<br>
<br>
She shrugged. &quot; What can I say, being dead does put a damper on one’s social calendar.&quot;<br>
<br>
His eyebrow arched at her comment. &quot; So the rumors are true then? You fell to the Harvester in Velious?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; That’s old news, my friend.&quot; Terolyn snickered softly. &quot; I would love to stay and catch up, but I’m here on business.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; I expected nothing else.&quot; He motioned her to follow as he turned and headed for an area more private. The smuggler Lord sat himself on one of the many plush cushions he had strewn about a corner of the cove.  &quot; So, what can I do for you Anari?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; First of all, I don’t use that name anymore.&quot;<br>
<br>
He nodded slowly, gesturing to the guild pin on the lapel of her cloak. &quot; Trying to be respectable?&quot;<br>
<br>
She laughed. &quot; Hardly. The Dragons provide me with what I need for the time being.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; And that would be?&quot;<br>
<br>
Her beautiful elven features darkened. &quot; You are still as curious as I remember, Anson. Haven’t you heard what curiosity did to the cat?&quot;<br>
<br>
 Anson cleared his throat nervously at the implication. &quot; So, what do you need from me this time, Rogue?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;An elixir,&quot; she took a pouch of coins from her belt and tossed it to him.  &quot; You most potent paralysis poison, on that can be ingested.&quot;<br>
<br>
He lifted his eyes from the pouch to the deadly woman before him. &quot; A mark? I didn’t realize you were back in the game.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; I’m not.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; A personal vendetta then? Going after the Harvester again are we?&quot;<br>
<br>
A sneer crossed her lips, and a soft growl sounded from the back of her throat. &quot; You ask too many questions, McBale. Why the sudden interest?&quot;<br>
<br>
He reached over to a box that lay not far from him, lifting the lid to expose the dozens of tiny bottles. &quot; I like to know what my poisons are being used for, purely selfish reasons I assure you. I enjoy hearing what they do to their intended victim.&quot; He removed a vial of a clear liquid from the chest and tossed it to Terolyn, who caught it easily out of the air. &quot; One drop of that mixed in a bottle of wine, or skin of ale, will render any who drink motionless in a matter a few minute. It will last long enough for you to slit their throats.&quot;<br>
<br>
She eyed the liquid inside the vial, a wicked smile replacing the sneer on her lips. &quot; And if I wanted it to last longer?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; Increase the dosage. But any more than a few drops and you risk the poison being detected through taste or smell.   I would suggest only a drop or two, and when your victim is immobilized administer the rest as needed.&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn slipped the vial into a pocket, and palmed an object unseen by McBale. &quot; I trust your discretion in this matter?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; My lips are sealed, my dear.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; Let’s make sure they are, shall we?&quot; Her hand snapped up, the serrated metal disk in her hand flying out toward the unsuspecting smuggler.  The throwing star imbedded itself in the man’s throat, blood seeping from beneath the metal disk as he fought for breath. Another deadly disk shot through the air, sinking into the flesh just beneath the other.<br>
<br>
Anson McBale collapsed onto his side, his dead eyes staring horrifically at her.<br>
<br>
Moving quickly she hurried out of the cove, the shouts of the alarm echoing through the pass as the smuggler guarding the entrance fell into a pool of his own blood and she dove into the water once again.<br>
<br>
<br>
