<br>
Her mind intent on her project, Terolyn dipped the lip of one of the goblets in a saucer of clear liquid. Moving the goblet to another shallow dish she laced the moist crystal with an opaque powder. Blowing gently on the glass she watched with satisfaction as the powder and liquid dried invisible against the goblet’s surface.<br>
<br>
A soft noise outside the hall alerted the rogue of the approach of someone, and as the door to the hall opened she covered the two saucers with her cloak. Terolyn looked up as Cresida entered the Dragons Guildhall.<br>
<br>
&quot; Terolyn!&quot; Cresida said in a surprised whisper when she noticed the Feir’Dal in the corner. &quot; I didn’t think anyone would be awake at the hour.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; I couldn’t sleep.&quot;<br>
<br>
The cleric raised a delicate eyebrow at her and at the contents of her table. &quot; So you thought you’d sit in a dark corner with a half-dozen empty glasses?&quot;<br>
<br>
She forced a smile and reached for a wine skin that hung off the back of her chair. &quot; I just finished working on something and thought I would have a drink.&quot; She poured the contents of the skin into two glasses, one the goblet she just finished tampering with. &quot; Would you care to join me for some Rathe Berry juice.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cresida hesitated a moment before crossing the room to sit across from Terolyn. She noticed the serious expression on her friends face and asked, &quot; Is everything alright?&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn chuckled. &quot; Getting better all the time.&quot; She lifted her glass from the table, indicating for Cresida to do the same. &quot; I’ve hear that congradulations are in order for you. Getting married and having a baby, you must be happy.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cresida nodded, taking the tampered goblet in hand. &quot; Aye, I am.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; Then I’d like to propose a toast. To getting everything we’ve wanted.&quot;<br>
<br>
Something about the way Terolyn spoke sent a chill up Cresida’s spine, and she watched the rogue intently as they both raised their glasses to their lips.<br>
<br>
Terolyn pushed the sudden feeling of regret to the back of her mind as her glass hovered a hair’s breadth above her crimson lips. Cresida trusted her, and did not seem to hesitate as she took a drink from the goblet. Guilt overwhelmed her momentarily, but she ignored the feeling and set her glass back onto the table’s surface.<br>
<br>
&quot; Terolyn, what is it?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; The gods do not smile on us tonight my friend.&quot; Terolyn said as she pulled the cloak of the table that hid the two saucers. &quot; I’m sorry. If only you had not returned when you did.&quot;<br>
<br>
Koa’Dal eyes narrowed in confusion a moment before a sudden numbness began to sweep through her body.<br>
<br>
Terolyn rose from the table, pouring what was left of the liquid back into its vial. &quot; A paralysis poison. The same that your beloved Pendragon used when he tried to kill me. A variation of course, but the same effect none the less.&quot; She pocketed the vial, her emerald eyes shining menacingly in the candle light. The powder she replaced in a small satchel. &quot; And a sedative, strong enough that it would send the largest barbarian into slumber for hours.&quot; She knelt before the now unmoving cleric and brushed a strand of hair from Cresida’s face. <br>
<br>
Cresida could find no words, and it was not from any effects of the poisons. Her eyes frantically scanned the face of the rogue before her, trying to find any trace of the friend she once knew in the hate filled features of the woman. <br>
<br>
&quot; Do not worry about your baby, the drugs should have no effect on it.&quot; Terolyn got to her feet, and gathered her things. She kissed Cresida on the top of her head. &quot; You should have let him die, Cresida. None of this would be happening if you had just let him die. But it does not matter now. By the time I am through with him, there will be nothing left for you to bring back.&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn watched the sedative take effect and the Koa’Dal slipped into unconsciousness. She looked at the elf’s frightened features for a moment before turning from the scene and exiting the hall. The test was successful, the mixture of the two drugs would be enough to bring down her unsuspecting prey. <br>
<br>
The hunt began.<br>
