Patches of moonlight illuminated the forest floor, filling the Faydark with silver light. Thought it was late and the moon would soon be setting in favor of the sun, a lone figure walked silently among the trees. She walked quickly, but without sound, obviously knowing the area well. Sapphire eyes glinted in the darkness beneath a black hooded cloak as she neared her destination and saw a light in the window. She had expected darkness at this hour. The figure spoke a syllable and vanished.<br>
<br>
A feeling of unease crept over Kassy as she approached the door of the Dragons' Hall. It hung slightly ajar, still moving. Invisible hands closed over the edge of the wooden door, pushing it slowly open. A single candle that stood on a table in the far corner lit the room, eerie shadows dancing over tables, chairs, and hearth-stones. Near the candle were several empty wine glasses. The Teir’Dal’s eyes fell then across the elven cleric lying motionless upon the stone floor.<br>
<br>
With the quickness of the elves, Kass was at her side. Cresida was breathing, her heartbeat calm, if a bit slow. Removing her long cloak, Kassy folded it and placed it beneath her head. She stood and looked at the table, lifting a glass. It appeared untampered with, just a wine glass. She put it back on the table, but picked it up again. From a pouch at her belt she took a pinch of silver dust and let it fall, drifting over the goblet as she murmured a few soft words. The glass began to glow purple... all but the rim, which remained clear. She set the glass on the table, not bothering to cast her enchantment upon the others, and knelt by the fallen Koada'dal.<br>
<br>
&quot;Cresida,&quot; she spoke the name quietly, fearing to wake the Dragons. &quot;Cresida, wake up...&quot; No response. <br>
<br>
The enchantress closed her eyes, searching her mind for the spell she desired. As the words came to her, she placed dark hands on the cleric's brow and over her heart. Kassy spoke, the spidery words of magic crackling in the air around her, &quot;Ar'anen halar. Et'intavaria. DiGrato b'las'io.&quot; The magic flowed through her and to the spell's target, striping the enchantments of sleep an paralysis. <br>
<br>
A moment passed, then two and still Cresida slept. Kassy began to fear that her spell would have no effect on ingested toxins when a movement caught her attention. Green eyes were looking up at her, confused and a little scared. &quot;Kassy...?&quot;<br>
<br>
The dark-skinned elf breathed a sigh of relief, &quot;Cresida, thank Tunare. What happened?&quot;<br>
<br>
Cresida looked up at the glasses sitting upon the table, her gaze falling curiously upon the one that still glowed faintly. &quot;Kassy, what are you doing here? And Terolyn,&quot; she asked, &quot;where is Terolyn?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I came here looking for her... she--&quot; Kassy's words died on her dark lips, ''Where is Minz?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Minz?&quot; the cleric looked puzzled, &quot;I don't know where he is--&quot;<br>
<br>
Her words were cut off as Kassy stood and turned toward the door. &quot;Do not eat or drink anything within the hall. Burn all of it. Boil every dish and piece of silverware the Dragons' own.&quot; She pulled a small sparkling object from a hidden pocket in her robe and tossed it to the cleric. Cresida's eyes widened as she caught the item and discovered it to be a large diamond. &quot;That will cover the cost of replacing it all. I should have known she'd do this...&quot;<br>
<br>
Before Cresida could even form a response, the enchantress had retrieved her cloak and was out the door and she was left to look from the gem in her hand to the poisoned glasses upon the table.<br>
<br>
&quot;Tunare guard us all,&quot; she whispered to the night. <br>
<br>
