<br>
&quot; What are you doing here?&quot;<br>
<br>
The rogue turned her head away from the master and student, looking to the erudite that approached.  Her smile rapidly faded. &quot; I should have sent word I was coming, I’m sorry Mongul.&quot;<br>
<br>
The necromancers face was stern. &quot; That still doesn’t answer my question Ana-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; It’s Terolyn now.&quot;<br>
<br>
He guffawed as he came to stand next to her, resting against the stone ledge. &quot; Anari, Terolyn… Did I ever know who you were?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; That’s not fair,&quot; Terolyn sighed.<br>
<br>
&quot; When has this life every been fair?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; And when did you get so cynical?&quot; She shook her head. &quot; Look, I’m sorry I came.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mongul grabbed her arm as she turned to leave. &quot; She asks about you, you know. All the time. She misses you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn glanced at his chiseled featured that seemed to have suddenly grown very old. &quot; And what about you?&quot;<br>
<br>
He smiled softly. &quot; Our time passed a long time ago. But she still needs you, she needs her mother.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ginger hair bounced as she shook her head again. &quot; She doesn’t need a mother like me.&quot; Gently pulling out of his grasp she took a few steps back. &quot; She’s not why I’m here. I need your help with someting, Mongul. There are others that could do it, but I know the quality would be the best if you were to do it.&quot;<br>
<br>
He nodded, recognizing the all-business look that now filled her face. &quot; You know I’ll help you where I can.&quot;<br>
<br>
She explained her idea to him, the necromancer nodding occasionally as she spoke. When she was finished he stared at her, trying to conceal his astonishment. &quot; It could work, though why you want to do this-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; I promise, someday I’ll tell you everything.&quot; Terolyn smiled hopefully. &quot; So you’ll do it?&quot;<br>
<br>
Mongul nodded. &quot; I’ll need to prepare things in my lab, but give me a day or two and everything will be ready.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; Excelent. That will give me enough time to carry out my end of things.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; And what about her?&quot; He looked down at the half-elf sparring with the Instructor. &quot; Will you stay long enough to at least say hello this time? Terolyn? Ana?&quot; He looked around, sighing when he saw he was alone.<br>
 <p><center><img src="http://deliz.clanpages.com/teroeqsig.jpg " border="0"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#464446><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uterolynlethan.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Terolyn Lethan</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/22/02 8:08:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisroleplaying.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=564.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://deliz.clanpages.com/kittyspaz.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Return to the Shadows</span><hr size=1> Even the normally bright moon of Luclin could nor penetrate the dark storm clouds that filled the nights sky of the mountains. Rain poured down around the rogue and her druid companion as they stepped out of the portal created by the druid’s magic, and within a matter of second both wood elves were soaked to the bone.   Terolyn ran beneath the shelter of one of the rings great stones, the druid following quickly behind. <br>
<br>
&quot; Perhaps we should wait until morning before we go looking for your friend,&quot; the druid shouted above a roar of thunder, &quot; At least wait until the storm has passed.&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn shook her head sending droplets of water flying from her hair. &quot; There’s no time. Now you’re sure this is where you brought him? A blind half-elf wearing the same guild pin as me?&quot;<br>
<br>
He nodded. &quot; Aye. Just this morning. He had me point him east, said he’d be able to follow the mountain wall to where he was going. I didn’t like leaving him on his own, but he insisted.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; Wait here for us. I should be back with him by nightfall tomorrow. You’ll be needed to get us out of here quickly.&quot; She tossed him a small satchel of coins. &quot; You’ll get the rest of your payment when my friend and I are out of these mountain. And something extra for your time.&quot; <br>
<br>
He eyes the pouch, knowing well the platinum piece it held inside, and nodded emphatically. &quot; Yes Ma’am!&quot;<br>
<br>
The black rain was nearly blinding as she headed eastward away from the druid ring. There was only one place in that direction that Minz was familiar enough with to get to on his own.  Lucky for her she knew the area just as well and was able to run the entire way along the mountain and through the pass. <br>
<br>
She reached the rocky ledge high about the expanse of water an hour after leaving the druid behind. The rain had subsided, yet the dark clouds had still not parted.  She knew the quickest way to her destination would be to swim across the lake, but in the dark it would be easy to get turned around and she did not have time to deal with the aqua goblins or undertow skeletons she knew would be beneath the water’s surface.<br>
<br>
Determined to reach Minz before sunrise she set out south, following the waters edge, her ravenscale boots gripping precariously at time on the water slick stones. Yet even the balance of a nimble rogue will succumb to the elements, and her footing slipped. She slid along the rocky slope, the stone tearing through her leggings and into the flesh of her leg, as she scrambled for a hand hold. Her descent stopped as she fingers managed to grab hold of a jagged rock jutting out, her feet dangled off a sheer drop above the water. <br>
<br>
Gasping to catch her breath, she climbed her way back up the slope to the ledge where she collapsed  onto the wet stones. A flash of lightning tore the sky open, spilling the contents of the clouds again.  Terolyn could not help but laugh at the situation as the rain splattered against her face.<br>
<br>
&quot; Hello?! Are you alright?&quot;<br>
<br>
Tilting her head back, she saw a rain drenched wood elf making his was across the stone toward her.  She propped herself onto an elbow as he came to kneel beside her. &quot; I’m fine.&quot;<br>
<br>
He looked to her leg and at the blood seeping from gashed on her hand. &quot; You do not look fine, Milady. Have you been wounded by the beats of this region?&quot;<br>
<br>
She chuckled. &quot; No, just a moment of clumsiness is all.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; I am Elmion Hendrys. My camp is near by, you are welcome to rest there while my companions and I tend to your wounds.&quot;<br>
<br>
With the realization she was not going anywhere else that night, she nodded and took the Feir’Dal’s offered hand.  Placing her arm around his shoulder he helped her move across the slippery ground and toward a fire that shone through the rain in the distance. <br>
<br>
&quot; Nyrien, Ghilanbiddle,&quot; Elmion called as they approached the camp. &quot; A hand if you will please.&quot;<br>
<br>
A white haired Koa’Dal stepped out of the tent and when he saw Terolyn he hurried to help Elmion carry her out of the rain. &quot; Goblins?&quot; <br>
<br>
She shook her head with a rueful  smile. &quot; Rock. I slipped.&quot;<br>
<br>
Pushing the flap of the tent aside, Elmion and the high elf helped her inside. The latter one smiled back. &quot; I am Nyrien, and I can assure you that there are many dangers in this land.&quot; He took her from the wood elf and guided her to a bed role. &quot; You may rest here if you like.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; HA!&quot; A some-what squeaky voice pitched in indignantly. &quot; One like that one stands no chance within this realm. The goblins shall skin her alive!!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; Pipe down, Ghil!!&quot; Elmion snapped at the gnome that laid on a bedroll across the tent as he knelt beside Terolyn as Nyrien helped her down to the bedroll. &quot; We have no quarrel with-&quot; He raised an eyebrow curiously at her. &quot; I don’t believe I caught your name.&quot;<br>
<br>
There was no sense lying. The Dragons may be searching for her if Cresida told them anything, but it would not matter. They could not stop her now. &quot; Terolyn.&quot;<br>
<br>
Both elves smiled. Nyrien chanted a few soft words of magic and a pale blue light encircled his hands.  He held them above her leg. &quot; Will you accept a healing from Tunare, Lady Terolyn?&quot;<br>
<br>
She nodded in response, her emerald eyes intent on the disgruntled gnome that stared right back at her.<br>
<br>
His little pale nose wrinkled in irritation when the light of healing encompassed her leg and the gash began to mend. &quot; What business do you have here?!! Trying to keep safe? Expecting us to fight your battles? Bah!!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; I search for the Pendragon of my order.&quot; She removed the guild pin from her lapel and allowed Elmion to inspect it. &quot; He is in grave danger from someone who seeks him. He would not know of this threat, and would not know of it until too late.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; Bah!!&quot; Ghilanbiddle rose from his bedroll and stormed out of the tent. <br>
<br>
&quot; There was a man this afternoon who passed by our camp.&quot; Elmion stated handing the pin back to her. &quot; We offer aid to any who make their way through this realm, and I remember him because he asked if he were heading in the right direction. I found it odd since most who come this way know where they are goin and which direction it is&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot; It took us a moment to realize that he was blind, but he did wear that same pin,&quot; Nyrien added. He took his hands away from her leg, revealing the smooth olive skin beneath the jagged tear in her pants. &quot; I have mended your wound, Lady Terolyn, though I’m afraid I can do nothing for your leggings.&quot;<br>
<br>
She flexed her leg, and smiled. &quot; My thanks, gentlemen. You did me not one kind service, but two. Now I know I am on the right trail of the Pendragon. Will you now do me one more service and join me in a drink?&quot; She reached into her pack and retrieved a wine skin from with. With a disarming smile she held it out for the two elves. &quot; It’s the least I can do after all you’ve done for me.&quot;<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
Ghil grumbled in the rain as he paced about the perimeter of the camp. Something about the woman had rubbed him the wrong way. Of course, he didn’t like anyone, but he liked her even less. Finally of a mind to tell his companions to get rid of her, he stormed back into the tent.<br>
<br>
&quot; Now look here you two! I-&quot;<br>
<br>
The words caught in his throat as he watched the woman rise from her feet, cleaning a blood stained dirk on the bed roll she sat on. Beside her lay the bodies of his friends, their throats slit and spilling their life’s blood.<br>
<br>
&quot; You are a rather rude little man, aren’t you - Ghil wasn’t it?&quot; Terolyn balanced the tip of the dirk on her finger as she stared menacingly at the gnome. &quot; Would it have killed you to be a little nicer to a stranger in need?&quot; She glanced at the corpses beside her and grinned wolfishly as she turned her piecing gaze back to the gnome. &quot; I suppose it would have.&quot; <br>
<br>
Her dirk suddenly flew through the air, imbedding itself through the stunned gnome’s foot and into the ground. He cried out in pain as he tried to pull the blade from his foot, not noticing as the woman he had had a bad feeling about got to her feet. With two strides she was crouching before him, her now mended hand tightening around his little throat. <br>
<br>
&quot; Your friends died quietly, painlessly, if it makes you feel better. You, on the other hand….&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
