The sun was just beginning to descend beneath mountains when the druid saw the woman approaching the druid ring. She was moving slowly, burdened by the man she half dragged. The druid rose quickly from resting spot beneath the shade of a tree and rushed to help her.<br>
<br>
&quot; What happened?&quot; He asked after taking in the wounds of both of them.<br>
<br>
&quot; We were ambushed by goblins,&quot; Terolyn let the druid take the semi-conscious Minz from her. She watched the druid sit Minz against the same tree he had been resting beneath and begin to examine the bloodied welt on his temple. Her fingers slipped into a hidden pocket on the inside of her cloak and brushed against the empty satchel of powder. The sedative had made it difficult to travel, but a few grains on the half-elf’s tongue, every time he showed any coherence, kept him docile enough. She had to move quickly though, for the powder was gone and the last dose would not last much longer.<br>
<br>
She took hold of the druid’s wrist as he began the healing chant. &quot; There is no time for that. We must move, now. You can heal him when we get to where we’re going.&quot;<br>
<br>
The druid looked up at her questioningly. &quot; I do not think it wise to move him any more without a healing. His injuries could be worse than they appear and we could do more harm than good.&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn softened her look, appearing concerned. &quot; I know that, but it wasn’t just goblins that ambushed us.&quot; She released her grip on his wrist and knelt beside him. She looked to Minz, her hand caressing  his cheek, and her lower lip trembling as she forced tears to her eyes. She spoke in a hushed voice, pleading emerald eyes turned to the druid. &quot; I need your help. I can’t protect him here.&quot;<br>
<br>
He nodded and patted her hand reassuringly. &quot; Alright, we’ll port out right away.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Minz moaned plaintively as the two Feir’Dal lifted him to his feet. The sedative was wearing off.<br>
<br>
&quot; You’ll have to hang on to him while I open the portal,&quot; the druid said as he took a few steps back and started the incantation.<br>
<br>
She nodded, not wanting to interrupt the spell. The air around them grew heavy as the magical energies surrounded the three of them. Terolyn tightened her grip on Minz as he shifted his weight, becoming more aware of his surroundings. Her fingernails dug into the skin of his arm, and she hissed in his ear, &quot; Don’t do anything foolish, Elandril. I could make this a lot worse than it has to be.&quot;<br>
<br>
The portal fell around the three travelers, the mountains fading away into a dark wood. Letting Minz drop to the cool grass beneath her feet, she closes the distance between her and the magically spent druid. &quot; Thank you my friend, you have probably save my life.&quot; Her fingers wove into his dark hair as she pressed herself against him, her lips hovering just above his. &quot; I told you I would reward you extra for your troubles.&quot; Confused, the druid did not resist as she began to kiss him, slowly, sensually.  He did not notice as she released the dagger hidden on her wrist into her palm.<br>
<br>
Behind the two elves, Minz propped himself onto an elbow. His head spun from the after effects of the drug but he knew what was to come. &quot; She’s going to kill you.&quot;<br>
<br>
The druid pulled his head back, his confusion even deeper at the half-elf’s words. &quot; Wha-&quot;<br>
<br>
Terolyn looked over her shoulder at Minz, her tongue running over her lips. &quot; Now you’ve gone and ruined my fun.&quot; Fingers clenched dark hair painfully and she plunged the dagger into the druids abdomen. His eyes widened in surprise and pain. She pulled him closer to her, burying the dagger to the hilt, blood spilling onto her hand as she slowly twisted the blade inside him. His scream echoed through the forest and she laughed in delight. <br>
<br>
Holding the poor elf on his feet she pulled the dagger upward, tearing through flesh and organs until the blade came to a stop against his lowest rib. A trickle of blood flowed from his lips as his life slowly ebbed from him. Her lips pressed again his again, her tongue licking away the blood with a soft growl. <br>
<br>
She left the dagger in him as she let him fall to his knees. Holding tight to his hair she removed the scimitar from the druid’s belt and held it to his throat. &quot; I meant it when I said you probably saved my life.&quot;  With one swipe of the blade she severed the head of the druid.<br>
<br>
With the head in hand she turned back to where Minz laid as the druid’s body fell onto its side. He tried to get to his hands and knees but she drove him back to the earth with a kick to the stomach. Chuckling darkly she dropped the head into the rogue’s lap. He cried out in disgust and shoved it off him but not before the blood soaked through his clothing. <br>
<br>
Blind eyes stared up at her. &quot; What’s happened to you Terolyn?&quot;<br>
<br>
A feral snarl escaped her and she reached down and grabbed him by the collar of his tunic. &quot; You happened to me!&quot; She lifted him from the ground with surprising strength for her size and slammed him against a tree, knocking the air from his lungs. &quot; You were my friend and I trusted you!&quot; <br>
<br>
She threw him back to the ground and turned him onto his stomach. Her knee dug into his back as she pulled his arms behind him and bound them tightly. Terolyn leaned into him, her bloodied lips brushing against his ear. &quot; You may be blind, Elandril, but by the gods you will see your beating heart in my hands before you die.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
