 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#403C50><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukhasirath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Khasirath</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.violentharvest.com/sigs/vh_anim.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 84<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/30/02 3:11:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisroleplaying.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=564.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.columbus.rr.com/harvest/khassmall.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Return to the Shadows</span><hr size=1> Khasirath walked through the city slowly, thoughtfully. Something teased at the edges of his senses. He paused between the dark stone buildings, watching the men and women going about their business. This was not a city he could call home, simply one that he was accepted in, and used as a resting place between hunts. He knew it well enough to find what he needed, but many of its streets remained unfamiliar to him.<br>
<br>
Standing beside a fountain, he tilted his head as if listening for something. It was not a sound, but a feeling, something he had not felt in quite a while. He half closed his eyes as he focused himself, attuning his power to the nagging sensation.<br>
<br>
A name came to him suddenly, and a wolfish grin stretched over his thin lips. “Ahhh,” he muttered to himself, “Anari.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath realized then that one of the guards of the city was watching him a bit too closely as he stood there in meditation. Accepted he might be, but Teir`Dal were still considered outsiders here, not to be trusted. Khasirath’s eyes narrowed, his grip tightening on the grip of his lance. The guard shifted uneasily, but stayed his post.<br>
<br>
Containing that snarl that was in his heart, Khasirath turned sharply away, and walked straight to the small room he had rented for his stay. The guard did not pursue him. The Reaper’s white eyes flashed silvery with his rage. Contemptible beasts, strutting about under the banner of that filthy creature Cazic-Thule, certain of their vaunted ‘superiority’. One day, and soon, they would be shown the power of Hate. They would be broken, and kneel before the Father after they paid for their interference.<br>
<br>
After locking the door to the small room, Khasirath laid his lance upon the narrow bed, and hung his heavy travel cloak by the door. He pulled off his gloves and unbuckled his bracers, placing them on the bed as well. From one of his packs he drew out an old box of Darkwood, its lid intricately carved with fine runes and symbols. Growling under his breath at the lack of a table or even a writing desk, he set the box down on the foot of the bed. He stilled his mind, and softly incanted a prayer in the Elder Teir’Dal as he opened the box, and lifted out the shallow bowl of Adamantite that had been imbued with Innoruuk’s blessing. Setting the bowl on the bed he drew a slim imbued Adamantite knife from it’s Koada`Dal leather sheath which was built into the lid of the box.<br>
<br>
Khasirath knelt beside the bed, and closed his eyes as he sank deep into prayer. As the Father’s Hate filled him, he focused it upon his bond with Anari, the link forged in blood and pain and the dark gifts of Innoruuk. Almost whispering the mantras of Hate, he opened his eyes once more, and lifted his arm above the bowl. He drew the keen edged blade deep across his wrist, across innumerable other scars from ceremonies and rituals of the past. His blood ran into the bowl, thick and hot, filling it halfway before he moved his arm away. He brought his wrist to his lips, licking along the cut to clean the blood away.<br>
<br>
Setting the blade beside the bowl, Khasirath stared into the depths of the blood, maintaining the clarity of Hate within him, and the bond with Anari. He was no Prophet, no scryer, but with the right tools and the Father’s Will, sometimes he was able to grasp a bit of insight.<br>
<br>
A long time passed, the thready sense of Anari’s presence mingling with the Reaper’s prayers and Innoruuk’s Hate. Khasirath’s breathing was slow and deep as he stared within the bowl, and the sensations became clearer. He could feel Anari’s hate, stronger than he had ever felt it before, and almost taste the vengeance-lust that filled her. Khasirath controlled the urge to smile at this, maintaining his control.<br>
<br>
An ache began, deep behind his eyes, within the scarred sockets. He refused to let it distract him. Resolutely he remained, watching the bowl, praying. The ache increased slowly, growing to a throbbing pain that stabbed in time with the slow beat of his heart. A slight hiss escaped him, but he did not falter.<br>
<br>
And then the vision came, not from the depths of the bowl, but from inside his eyes, the new eyes his Lord had given him. The still surface of the blood was merely a background on which the vision rested.<br>
<br>
Khasirath saw, as if from Anari’s own sight, the crumpled form of the Dragon’s blind Jester. Within himself he felt the utter madness of unbridled hate in her heart as she looked upon the mongrel Rogue. Like whispers in his mind he heard her plans for Minz, and the smile did come to his lips then.<br>
<br>
The vision was brief, only a flash of sight really. Suddenly the pain behind Khasirath’s eyes twisted like a jagged knife into his brain, and he gritted his teeth hard to keep from crying out. His sight flashed deepest blood red, and then all to black.<br>
<br>
The power of Innoruuk’s hate within him receded as a tide, and Khasirath reached forward carefully, grasping the edges of the bowl. He lifted it slowly to his lips, and drank the cooling blood. Softly he muttered one last prayer as he set the bowl back down.<br>
<br>
Unsteadily Khasirath stood, holding onto the edge of the bed. He sat down at the head of the bed, his breath faster, struggling for control. Squeezing his eyes shut he focused on the hate within him, and waited. His breathing stilled once more, his heart stopped its racing. A long while he sat, before opening his eyes.<br>
<br>
At first all he saw were shadows, vague outlines of the bed and the walls, the darkness of his cloak on the wall. But steadily his vision cleared and returned. Within a few minutes all was well.<br>
<br>
He stood once more, and carefully cleaned the bowl and blade before returning them to the box. He put it back into his bag, and clasped his cloak around his shoulders. Lifting up his lance, he left the room once more, locking the door behind him. In the hall he called upon the shadows, cloaking himself within their magic.<br>
<br>
The sense of Anari’s presence was much clearer now, and as he walked the streets he concentrated on it, letting it guide his wanderings until he came to a large dark house. Finding a quiet spot he watched and waited. The house in some small ways made him think for a moment of home. Of course, it could not truly compare to the manse of House S`Therik, but an aura of power and dignity not unfamiliar seemed to linger about it.<br>
<br>
He doubted it would be an easy place to enter, but with patience, an opportunity would come. And as an elder race, patience was something the Reaper of the Violent Harvest had to spare.<br>
